post_text:
FYI: Resource from Partnership for Maternal and Child Health of Northern NJ

We have an exciting free workshop coming up at the Partnership that I hope you will share. Teen Speak for Parents is a free weekly one-hour interactive workshop for parents or guardians of teens and pre-teens to learn strategies to discuss sensitive topics with their teens. Topics include healthy relationships, substance abuse prevention, and making good choices. There are four online sessions in the program and the next course begins on August 6 at 5 pm. I included the video below that shares more details. Parents and guardians can register at http://augustteenspeak.eventbrite.com

Attention Members of the Manchester Community:

We understand that many families have been impacted by the COVID-19 pandemic in several ways including facing financial hardships, loss of employment, or dealing with grief and loss. We want you to know that we are here with you and would like to share that the Falcons’ Lounge School Based Youth Service Program, a program funded by the NJ Dept of Children and Families, is still open and available to offer assistance with accessing resources for any of your needs. You can reach Michelle Defreitas at 732-470-0218 or Catarina Sousa at 201-421-8306 for further assistance.

Welcome to our Guided Meditation through the forest.
This tranquil activity invites you to take a moment to relax and be present. Guided meditation is a mindfulness technique in which an instructor leads you through a meditation exercise. This type of meditation allows mental clarity and focus as you concentrate on the instructor's voice and any accompanying sounds and imagery. Stress and anxiety is reduced through the practice of deep breathing and muscle relaxation, experienced within the guided meditation session. Continual self care through meditation can help improve one's overall wellness. Please enjoy this activity.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1ypzy2diLQj5emFMSgIZsXrILd7l1xdBq/view

post_text: Manchester Supports Pinwheels for Prevention of Child Abuse: In 2008, Prevent Child Abuse America introduced the pinwheel as the new national symbol for child abuse prevention through Pinwheels for Prevention®. The pinwheel symbolizes whimsy and childlike notions and serves as the physical embodiment, or reminder, of the great childhoods we want for all children. Try this DIY pinwheel activity or printable coloring sheet with your family in support of Child Abuse Prevention. Learn more at PreventChildAbuse.org. If you suspect a child might be abused or neglected, call the NJ Child Abuse Hotline 1-877-NJ ABUSE (652-2873). #SBYSP #SafeHealthyConnected

post_text: Earth Day was first celebrated 50 years ago on April 22, 1970, and is credited with launching the modern environmental movement. This year’s theme is climate action. Earth Day led to passage of landmark environmental laws in the United States, including the Clean Air, Clean Water and Endangered Species Acts. Many countries soon adopted similar laws, and in 2016, the United Nations chose Earth Day as the day to sign the Paris Climate Agreement into force.

post_text:
Celebration of Poetry Month continues. Today we highlight Walt Whitman.

According to Walt Whitman, “To have great poets there must be great audiences too,” and Whitman is certainly one of those great poets. His most famous work is Leaves of Grass (1855, 1891-92), in which he celebrated democracy, nature, love, and friendship. One of those poems is "I Hear America Singing".

Learn more about Walt Whitman here https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/walt-whitman

Senior Isaiah Sparkes has been accepted to the United State Military Academy at West Point. For four years, Isaiah has been an example of hard work and dedication both academically and athletically. For those who don’t know, the application and interview process is a long and difficult road. Being accepted to West Point is an honor. Isaiah thanks his family, teachers, coaches, peers, and the Manchester community as a whole for their continued support.

MRHS is extremely proud of Isaiah! Congratulations!

Celebrated on March 14 each (yes, that’s 3-14), National Pi Day not only commemorates a very special number, but also celebrates the birthday of the great scientist and mathematician Albert Einstein. Pi was first calculated by Archimedes of Syracuse (287–212 BC), one of the greatest mathematicians of the ancient world.

post_text: Rosa Parks was on a bus in Montgomery, Alabama in 1955, when the bus driver asked her to stand up and give her seat to a white man. Parks, a black seamstress, refused and in doing so sparked an entire civil rights movement in America.

post_text: Marie Curie was a pioneering physicist and scientist, who coined the term radioactivity, discovered two new elements (radium and polonium) and developed a portable x-ray machine. She was the first person (not woman) who has won two separate Noble Prizes, one for physics and another for chemistry, and to this day Curie is the only person, regardless of gender, to receive Noble prizes for two different sciences.

post_text: Anne Frank (1929 – 1945) is the author of one of the most honest, powerful and poignant accounts of World War II, The Diary of Ann Frank. The Franks were a Jewish family living in Germany, then Austria throughout Hitler’s rise to power. The family hid in a secret annex with four other people throughout the war but were discovered and sent to concentration camps in 1944. Out of the Frank family, only Anne’s father survived, and he made the decision to publish Anne’s diary, written when she was just a young teenager.

post_text: Women's History Month: Amelia Earhart was an American aviator who set many flying records and championed the advancement of women in aviation. She became the first woman to fly solo across the Atlantic Ocean, and the first person ever to fly solo from Hawaii to the U.S. mainland. During a flight to circumnavigate the globe, Earhart disappeared somewhere over the Pacific in July 1937.

Manchester sports were extremely successful this week. Both the boys' and girls' basketball teams clinched their league titles. This week they will be playing their last regular season games; boys will play Becton at home on Tuesday 2/25 at 5 p.m. The girls will play at home on Thursday 2/27 at 5 p.m.
On the Wrestling front, Peret Shed took first place in the Districts and is on his way to the Regions this Friday and Saturday at West Milford High School. Winter Track is headed back to the second round of the states this weekend in Toms River. Congratulations to all our winter sports teams!

STEM NIGHTS AT MRHS:
Join us for an evening of hands-on science, math, and engineering activities for students and families. There will be four STEM Nights; Tuesday, March 10, March 24, April 21, and May 12, beginning at 7:00 p.m. We have something for EVERYONE no matter what age, so bring the whole family. Take part in our night of STEM challenges and test your design skills against others in a friendly, fun competition environment. ACTIVITIES: Makey Makey, Blinkey Bugs, Tiny Dancers, Cork Launchers, Robotics, 3D Printing, and more.

post_text: The New Jersey Seal of Biliteracy program recognizes bilingual and multilingual students. To achievie the Seal, students must demonstrate that they are able to speak, read, comprehend, & write in 2 or more languages at a high level of proficiency. MRHS takes great pride in the diversity of its student body, and has decided to have juniors and seniors pursue the Seal. This year 2 juniors and 6 seniors have qualified through AAPPL testing. Four students qualified for Arabic and 4 in Spanish. After this successful start we plan to test twice as many students next year to further increase the number who are able to achieve the Seal of Biliteracy.

Congratulations to Shani Gerald, member of the MRHS Girls Basketball Team and new record holder!
Gerald made ten 3 pointers against Elmwood Park on Tuesday and in doing so is now the school record holder for career 3 point field goals, 3 point field goals in a season, and 3 point field goals in a single game. She is also currently ranked #1 in New Jersey for 3 point field goals made this season.

post_text: Legos have entertained children and adults for nearly 70 years. Legos are used to make toy buildings, vehicles, creatures, machines, anything imaginable — and they can be taken apart and put back together as often as you’d like. That means endless creative play. post_text: International Holocaust Remembrance Day is an international memorial day on 27 January commemorating the tragedy of the Holocaust that occurred during the Second World War. It commemorates the genocide that resulted in the deaths of 6 million Jews and 11 million others, by the Nazi regime and its collaborators.

The 14th Annual Passaic County Teen Life Conference was held at William Paterson University on December 13, 2019. This conference, hosted by Planned Parenthood and the Family Life Institute, invited students to write an essay answering the following: "What suggestions do you have to make a positive change at your school or with the educational system as a whole?" Of all of the schools invited to attend this conference in Passaic County, a Manchester Regional High School student won 2nd place in the essay contest. Congratulations to Julio Suncar!
#SBYSP #SAFEHEALTHYCONNECTED

post_text: This day in history: The Boston Tea Party was a political protest that occurred on December 16, 1773, at Griffin's Wharf in Boston, Massachusetts. American colonists, frustrated and angry at Britain for imposing “taxation without representation,” dumped 342 chests of tea, imported by the British East India Company into the harbor.

post_text: November 23 is celebrated as Fibonacci day because when the date is written in the mm/dd format (11/23), the digits in the date form a Fibonacci sequence: 1,1,2,3. A Fibonacci sequence is a series of numbers where a number is the sum of the two numbers before it.
